Windows NAT Denial of Service Vulnerability - CVE-2013-3182  
-----------------------------------------------------------
  
<span></span>
A denial of service vulnerability exists in the Windows NAT Driver that could cause the target system to stop responding until restarted.
  
To view this vulnerability as a standard entry in the Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures list, see [CVE-2013-3182](http://www.cve.mitre.org/cgi-bin/cvename.cgi?name=cve-2013-3182).
  
#### Mitigating Factors
  
Microsoft has not identified any mitigating factors for this vulnerability.
  
#### Workarounds
  
Microsoft has not identified any workarounds for this vulnerability.
  
#### FAQ
  
**What is the scope of the vulnerability?**   
This is a denial of service vulnerability.
  
**What causes the vulnerability?**   
The vulnerability is caused when the Windows NAT Driver service in Windows Server 2012 does not properly handle specially crafted ICMP packets leading to memory corruption.
  
**What** **is Windows NAT Driver service?**   
The Windows NAT Driver (winnat) service provides network address translation (NAT) in Windows. The service is used by remote access features such as DirectAccess running on Windows Server 2012.
  
**What is** **Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP)?**   
Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) is an error reporting and diagnostic utility and is considered a required part of any IP implementation. For more information, see [Microsoft Knowledge Base Article 170292](http://support.microsoft.com/kb/170292).
  
**What might an attacker use the vulnerability to do?**   
An unauthenticated attacker who successfully exploited this vulnerability could cause the target system to stop responding until restarted.
  
**How could an attacker exploit the** **vulnerability?**   
An unauthenticated attacker could send specially crafted ICMP packets to the target server.
  
**What systems are primarily at risk from the vulnerability?**   
Windows Server 2012 servers are affected by this vulnerability.
  
**What does the update do?**   
The update addresses the vulnerability by correcting the way that the Windows NAT Driver service validates memory addresses when handling specially crafted ICMP packets.
  
**When this security bulletin was issued, had this vulnerability been publicly disclosed?**   
No. Microsoft received information about this vulnerability through coordinated vulnerability disclosure.
  
**When this security bulletin was issued, had Microsoft received any reports that this vulnerability was being exploited?**   
No. Microsoft had not received any information to indicate that this vulnerability had been publicly used to attack customers when this security bulletin was originally issued.
  
